WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.960
This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:06.360 --> 00:11.060
For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:11.520 --> 00:20.840
This is Anne of Green Gables by L.M. Montgomery, Chapter 35, read by Sandy in Winter Park, Florida, February 2006.

00:22.000 --> 00:27.260
Anne's homesickness wore off, greatly helped in the wearing by her weekend visits home.

00:27.260 --> 00:34.720
As long as the open weather lasted, the Avonlea students went out to Carmody on the New Branch Railway every Friday night.

00:35.400 --> 00:42.500
Diana and several other Avonlea young folks were generally on hand to meet them, and they all walked over to Avonlea in a merry party.

00:43.320 --> 00:55.040
Anne thought those Friday evening gypsyings over the autumnal hills in the crisp golden air, with the home lights of Avonlea twinkling beyond, were the best and dearest hours in the whole week.

00:55.740 --> 01:01.160
Gilbert Blythe nearly always walked with Ruby Gillis, and carried her satchel for her.

01:01.480 --> 01:06.800
Ruby was a very handsome young lady, now thinking herself quite as grown up as she really was.

01:07.220 --> 01:14.260
She wore her skirts as long as her mother would let her, and did her hair up in town, though she had to take it down when she went home.

01:14.900 --> 01:20.060
She had large, bright blue eyes, a brilliant complexion and a plump, showy figure.

01:20.060 --> 01:26.060
She laughed a great deal, was cheerful and good-tempered, and enjoyed the pleasant things of life, frankly.

01:27.640 --> 01:32.380
But I shouldn't think she was the sort of girl Gilbert would like, whispered Jane to Anne.

01:32.760 --> 01:37.200
Anne did not think so either, but she would not have said so for the Avery Scholarship.

01:37.400 --> 01:47.080
She could not help thinking, too, that it would be very pleasant to have such a friend as Gilbert to jest and chatter with, and exchange ideas about books and studies and ambitions.

01:47.080 --> 01:55.980
Gilbert had ambitions, she knew, and Ruby Gillis did not seem the sort of person with whom such could be profitably discussed.

01:56.940 --> 02:00.260
There was no silly sentiment in Anne's ideas concerning Gilbert.

02:00.940 --> 02:05.680
Boys were, to her, when she thought about them at all, merely possible good comrades.

02:06.100 --> 02:11.820
If she and Gilbert had been friends, she would not have cared how many other friends he had, nor with whom he walked.

02:11.820 --> 02:21.240
She had a genius for friendship, girlfriends she had in plenty, but she had a vague consciousness that masculine friendship might also be a good thing,

02:21.600 --> 02:27.320
to round out one's conceptions of companionship and furnish broader standpoints of judgment and comparison.

02:28.140 --> 02:32.480
Not that Anne could have put her feelings on the matter into just such clear definition,

02:32.760 --> 02:39.980
but she thought that if Gilbert had ever walked home with her from the train, over the crisp fields and along the ferny byways,

02:39.980 --> 02:47.980
they might have had many and merry and interesting conversations about the new world that was opening around them and their hopes and ambitions therein.

02:48.960 --> 02:56.800
Gilbert was a clever young fellow, with his own thoughts about things and a determination to get the best out of life and put the best into it.

02:57.840 --> 03:02.740
Ruby Gillis told Jane Andrews that she didn't understand half the things Gilbert Blythe said.

03:02.740 --> 03:12.460
He talked just like Anne Shirley did when she had a thoughtful fit on, and for her part she didn't think it any fun to be bothering about books and that sort of thing when you didn't have to.

03:12.840 --> 03:20.780
Frank Stockley had lots more dash and go, but then he wasn't half as good looking as Gilbert, and she really couldn't decide which she liked best.

03:22.020 --> 03:29.820
In the academy, Anne gradually drew a little circle of friends about her, thoughtful, imaginative, ambitious students like herself.

03:30.600 --> 03:43.460
With the rose-red girl, Stella Maynard, and the dream girl, Priscilla Grant, she soon became intimate, finding the latter pale, spiritual-looking maiden to be full to the brim of mischief and pranks and fun,

03:43.720 --> 03:50.540
while the vivid black-eyed Stella had a heart full of wistful dreams and fancies, as aerial and rainbow-like as Anne's own.

03:53.340 --> 03:58.880
After the Christmas holidays, the Avonlea students gave up going home on Fridays and settled down to hard work.

03:58.880 --> 04:09.920
By this time, all the Queen's scholars had gravitated into their own places in the ranks, and the various classes had assumed distinct and settled shadings of individuality.

04:10.180 --> 04:20.180
Certain facts had become generally accepted. It was admitted that the medal contestants had practically narrowed down to three, Gilbert Blythe, Anne Shirley, and Lewis Wilson.

04:20.760 --> 04:25.460
The Avery Scholarship was more doubtful, any one of a certain six being a possible winner.

04:25.960 --> 04:33.560
The bronze medal for mathematics was considered as good as won by a fat, funny little upcountry boy with a bumpy forehead and a patched coat.

04:34.740 --> 04:45.460
Ruby Gillis was the handsomest girl of the year at the Academy. In the second-year classes, Stella Maynard carried off the palm for beauty, with small but critical minority in favor of Anne Shirley.

04:46.060 --> 04:58.060
Ethel Marr was admitted by all competent judges to have the most stylish modes of hairdressing, and Jane Andrews, plain, plodding, conscientious Jane, carried off the honors in the domestic science course.

04:58.640 --> 05:11.960
Even Josie Pye attained a certain preeminence as the sharpest-tongued young lady in attendance at Queen's, so it may be fairly stated that Miss Stacy's old pupils held their own in the wider arena of the academic course.

05:12.960 --> 05:24.180
Anne worked hard and steadily. Her rivalry with Gilbert was as intense as it had ever been in Avonlea School, although it was not known in the class at large, but somehow the bitterness had gone out of it.

05:24.400 --> 05:33.020
Anne no longer wished to win for the sake of defeating Gilbert, rather for the proud consciousness of a well-won victory over a worthy foeman.

05:33.940 --> 05:39.560
It would be worthwhile to win, but she no longer thought life would be insupportable if she did not.

05:40.440 --> 05:51.000
In spite of lessons, the students found opportunities for pleasant times. Anne spent many of her spare hours at Beachwood and generally ate her Sunday dinners there and went to church with Miss Barry.

05:51.720 --> 05:58.780
The latter was, as she admitted, growing old, but her black eyes were not dim nor the vigor of her tongue in the least abated.

05:59.220 --> 06:04.940
But she never sharpened the latter on Anne, who continued to be a prime favorite with the critical old lady.

06:04.940 --> 06:08.560
That Anne girl improves all the time, she said.

06:08.560 --> 06:18.580
I get tired of other girls. There is such a provoking and eternal sameness about them. Anne has as many shades as a rainbow, and every shade is the prettiest while it lasts.

06:19.060 --> 06:30.380
I don't know that she is as amusing as she was when she was a child, but she makes me love her and I like people who make me love them. It saves me so much trouble in making myself love them.

06:31.400 --> 06:41.580
Then, almost before anybody realized it, spring had come. Out in Avonlea, the Mayflowers were peeping pinkly out on the seer barrens where snow wreaths lingered.

06:42.140 --> 06:50.540
And the mist of green was on the woods and in the valleys. But in Charlottetown, harassed Queen's students thought and talked only of examinations.

06:51.120 --> 07:00.380
It doesn't seem possible that the term is nearly over, said Anne, while last fall it seemed so long to look forward to. A whole winter of studies and classes.

07:00.800 --> 07:07.220
And here we are with the exams looming up next week. Girls, sometimes I feel as if those exams meant everything.

07:07.620 --> 07:15.500
But when I look at the big buds swelling on those chestnut trees and the misty blue air at the end of the streets, they don't seem half so important.

07:16.440 --> 07:19.960
Jane and Ruby and Josie, who had dropped in, did not take this view of it.

07:19.960 --> 07:28.960
To them, the coming examinations were constantly very important indeed. Far more important than chestnut buds or Maytime hazes.

07:29.420 --> 07:35.340
It was all very well for Anne, who was sure of passing at least, to have her moments of belittling them.

07:35.740 --> 07:42.760
But when your whole future depended on them, as the girls truly thought theirs did, you could not regard them philosophically.

07:43.360 --> 07:50.560
I've lost seven pounds in the last two weeks, sighed Jane. It's no use to say don't worry. Worrying helps you some.

07:50.860 --> 07:59.260
It seems as if you were doing something when you're worrying. It would be dreadful if I failed to get my license after going to Queen's all winter and spending so much money.

08:00.160 --> 08:07.340
I don't care, said Josie Pye. If I don't pass this year, I'm coming back next. My father can't afford to send me.

08:07.340 --> 08:16.200
And Frank Stockley says that Professor Tremaine said Gilbert Blythe was sure to get the medal, and that Emily Clay would likely win the Avery Scholarship.

08:17.040 --> 08:27.400
That may make me feel badly tomorrow, Josie, laughed Anne, but just now I honestly feel that as long as I know the violets are coming out all purple down in the hollow below Green Gables,

08:27.840 --> 08:34.960
and that little ferns are poking their heads up in Lover's Lane, it's not a great deal of difference whether I win the Avery or not.

08:34.960 --> 08:43.100
I've done my best, and I begin to understand what is meant by the joy of the strife. Next to trying and winning, the best thing is trying and failing.

08:43.700 --> 08:54.620
Girls, don't talk about exams. Look at that arch of pale green sky over those houses, and picture to yourself what it must look like over the purpley dark beech woods back of Avonlea.

08:55.480 --> 08:59.180
What are you going to wear for commencement, Jane? asked Ruby practically.

08:59.900 --> 09:11.580
Jane and Josie both answered at once, and the chatter drifted into a side eddy of fashions, but Anne, with her elbows on the windowsill, her soft cheek laid against her clasped hands,

09:11.580 --> 09:26.000
and her eyes filled with visions looked out unheatingly across city roof and spire to that glorious dome of sunset sky, and wove her dreams of a possible future from the golden tissue of youth's own optimism.

09:27.100 --> 09:37.740
All the beyond was hers, with its possibilities lurking rosily in the oncoming years, each year a rose of promise to be woven into an immortal chaplet.

09:37.740 --> 09:42.940
And that's the end of chapter 35.

